The issue with the code is that it is using a `Scanner` to read the file, which is not the best approach for reading a text file. Instead, you should use a `BufferedReader` to read the file. Here's the updated code using `BufferedReader.readLine`:
```java
import java.io.BufferedReader;
import java.io.FileReader;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

public class RecordManager {
    private List<Record> resultArr;
    private int size;

    public RecordManager() {
        resultArr = new ArrayList<Record>();
        size = 0;
    }

    public void readResultData() throws IOException {
        BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("resultdata.txt"));
        String line;
        while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) {
            String[] fields = line.split("#");
            String athlete = fields[0];
            String country = fields[1];
            int pos = Integer.parseInt(fields[2]);
            String record = fields[3];
            String raceTime = fields[4];

            if ("WRC".equals(record)) {
                resultArr.add(new WorldRecord(athlete, country, pos, raceTime));
            } else if ("OLR".equals(record)) {
                resultArr.add(new OlympicRecord(athlete, country, pos, raceTime));
            } else {
                resultArr.add(new RaceResult(athlete, country, pos, raceTime));
            }
            size++;
        }
        br.close();
    }
}
```
With this updated code, you should be able to read the text file without any issues.
